	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
				 <p><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>Sept 13&#47;5613</date> A. M.</p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee> <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Dear Sir&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Though I promised you when I was in your city to<lb/> <sic>comunicate</sic> to you&#44; <del>so could I not</del> being not able to comply with your<lb/> request&#44; to my regret&#44; owing to a famine of news&#44; I deferred it.<lb/>  As <sic>agreable</sic> the task would be to me&#44; and as <sic>meagre</sic><lb/> &#38; barren even my <sic>comunication</sic> would have been&#44; should I<lb/> have <sic>knowen</sic> something important enough of recording<lb/> in your paper&#44; I certainly would have complied with.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Would I have <sic>knowen</sic> that your correspondents here&#44;<lb/> would not have informed you&#44; as regards the dedication<lb/> of the synagogue in <placeName><hi rend="underline">Wmsburg</hi></placeName> in its proper time&#44; I would<lb/> have taken the liberty of doing so&#44; a I have <sic>wittnesed</sic><lb/> the consecration.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As regards me&#44; I can give you the greatest satisfaction<lb/> of my situation.  The institution of <persName>Mr Sivor</persName> &#40;the proprie<lb/>tor&#41; <sic>encreases</sic> <sic>dayly</sic>.  We held yesterday our examination&#44;<lb/> the first since our existence &#40;3 months&#33;&#41; which result<lb/> to give&#44; would be immodest from me to <sic>comunicate</sic>&#59;<lb/> as you will hear of it &#40;&#63;&#33;&#41; Some of the gentlemen of the<lb/> committee were <persName>Mr Jones</persName> or <persName>Jonas</persName> and <persName>Dr Friedlein</persName> &#40;who former<lb/>ly was a <sic>candidat</sic> of Rabbinism&#44; and a pedagogue in the<lb/> house of <persName>Mr Lorsh</persName> of <placeName>Munich&#44; Bavaria</placeName>&#41; which we both <del>eminint</del><lb/> eminent &#38; high learned gentlemen.  The minor class<lb/> I instruct.  Also the sacred language&#44; to the little sons<lb/> of <persName>Judah</persName>&#44; with the translation of the Bible <add>Hebrew</add> &#38; <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> every <date><sic>sunday</sic></date> is my task.  I give them&#44; then a lecture on</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>Judaism&#44; which always <sic>in</sic> followed &#38; repeated&#44; with more<lb/> strength by our orthodoxish Proprietor <persName>Mr. Livor</persName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The children some 12 or 13 years old&#44; coming from other<lb/> schools to ours are not able of reading hebrew&#44; nor translate<lb/> a chapter of the pentateuch correct.  I do not com<lb/>prehend&#44; how that is&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">But the skillful Teacher&#44; who without fatiguing <sic>know&#39;s</sic>&#44;<lb/> how to arrange such labours <sic>displayes</sic> his talents of<lb/> showing the Hebrew juveniles&#44; what their future destinat<lb/>ion to what <placeName>Israel</placeName> is chosen &#38; dedicated &#38;c.  By some<lb/> of children&#44; it had effected already.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">But the most what is to deplore&#44; the moral instruc<lb/>tion the child receives in school is all forgotten when<lb/> the child returns home&#44; to the parental roof &#38; <sic>wittnessed</sic><lb/> how busily the father is engaged on the <date>sabbath</date> in selling<lb/> goods&#59; how the mother stands in the kitchen preparing<lb/> food &#40;as I saw on <add>Hebrew</add>&#41;&#33;  Such is our Judaism&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I would like very much to occupy your attention a<lb/> little longer&#44; but the time of our devotion draws nigh.<lb/>  I wish you to the beginning of the year&#44; that the<lb/> Lord of all flesh may <sic>grand</sic> you life for many years<lb/> to come&#44; to enjoy good health &#38; that the seed which you<lb/> <sic>distralated</sic><add>&#63;</add> in your Occident may not by its readers<lb/> fall of barren soil&#59; that your toil &#38; labour may<lb/> be blessed <add>Hebrew</add>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Please dear Sir&#33;  I rejoice me&#44; with your comu&#44;<lb/><sic>nication</sic> and you will oblige yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)">brotherly connected in faith</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">Solomon Weil</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(9)"><placeName>No 262 Fifth Street</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><placeName>near Avenue C.</placeName></p>
		</body>
